defaultIn this submission we argue that there is no evidence that sponsored academies have proved more effective than maintained schools in raising standards. 
defaultAnecdotes about individual schools do not constitute evidence. 
defaultWe further argue that there is evidence to suggest that sponsored academies have not contributed to closing attainment gaps 
defaultbut
default that by 
defaultmaking possible (as own admission authority schools)
default 
defaultmore
default socio-economic selection they are
default likely to make this situation worse.
default We agree with the recent statement by 
defaultAndreas Schleicherdefault that 
default“defaultThe UK demonstrates that increasing school choice and competition does not improve standards”default&#xa0;
default1.2
default              
defaultWe maintain that the p
defaultrocess of academy conversion and the es
defaulttablishment of free schools has
default been characterised by a serious democratic deficit, by a substantial waste of public money and by entirely unproductive levels of conflict within local communities.
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default              
defaultWe consider tha
defaultt 
defaultthe Secretary of State’s approach to intervention is wholly inadequate and demonstrates a failure to understand how the process of school improvement actually works. We consider that there is much more to be learned from the success of collaborative prog
defaultrammes such as 
defaultthe 
defaultLondon and City Challenge
defaults
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default              
defaultThe Committee’s terms of reference assume the continuation and the further expansion of the academy programme. SEA argues that this is not a sustainable position and 
defaultthat a new settlement is required whic
defaulth addresses the confusion and fragmentation that now characterises the English school system.
